---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { getPost } from '../../data/posts';
import { engageHref, products, withBase } from '../../site.config';

const post = getPost('vj-trust-local-audio')!;
const siteOrigin = Astro.site?.origin ?? 'https://sollabs.tech';
const structuredData = [
  {
    '@type': 'BlogPosting',
    headline: post.title,
    datePublished: post.date,
    description: post.description,
    author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'Sol Labs' },
    publisher: { '@id': `${siteOrigin}/#organization` },
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title={`${post.title} · Sol Labs`}
  description={post.description}
  current="blog"
  ogType="article"
  publishedTime={post.date}
  structuredData={structuredData}
>
  <article class="page-wrap">
    <div class="prose">
      <p class="meta">{post.date} · {post.icp}</p>
      <h1>{post.title}</h1>
      <p>
        Working VJs do not romanticize “the cloud.” Unreleased edits are livelihood. Stage tools are
        judged by whether media is local, fast, and under the operator’s control — not by a signup
        wall.
      </p>

      <h2>Local media is the culture</h2>
      <p>
        On the Resolume forums, cloud-only OneDrive or Dropbox files are a known way to freeze Arena
        while the OS hydrates media (
        <a href="https://resolume.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=24016">OneDrive freeze thread</a>,
        <a href="https://resolume.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=19179">sync hang discussion</a>). The
        advice from practitioners is blunt: keep performance media on local disks. Adjacent tooling
        markets the same promise — local database, no account (
        <a href="https://github.com/FyodorKrasniy/stagehand-vj">stagehand-vj</a>).
      </p>

      <h2>Upload is the trust cliff</h2>
      <p>
        A browser visualizer that requires uploading stems asks the operator to believe a stranger’s
        retention policy on the worst night of the tour. Even if the shaders are excellent, the trust
        model fails first. Content control shows up elsewhere in VJ ops too — rental machines, theft,
        and who can touch the library (
        <a href="https://resolume.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=13989">securing content thread</a>).
      </p>

      <h2>What private in-browser inference has to prove</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Load from local files for the core path</li>
        <li>Analyze with Web Audio on-device</li>
        <li>Offer real controls (EQ, MIDI, editable GLSL) — not a toy</li>
        <li>Make the trust model obvious in the first minute</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        That is the
        <a href={products.slerp.href}>Slerp</a> receipt: audio-reactive WebGL with local playback and
        analysis. Shader craft is secondary to “your set does not leave the machine.”
      </p>

      <p>
        <a class="btn btn--primary" href={engageHref}>Book a call</a>
        {' '}
        <a class="btn btn--secondary" href={withBase('/outcomes/private-vj-inference/')}>Private VJ outcome</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
